## đź”µ Encoding and Decoding

| Command | What it Does | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `base64 -d file` | Decode base64 encoded file | `base64 -d data.txt` |
| `base64 file` | Encode file to base64 | `base64 data.txt` |
| `echo "text" \| base64` | Encode a text string to base64 | `echo "hello" \| base64` |
| `echo "string" \| base64 -d` | Decode a base64 string directly | `echo "SGVsbG8=" \| base64 -d` |
| `tr 'A-Za-z' 'N-ZA-Mn-za-m' < file` | Decode ROT13 encoded text | `tr 'A-Za-z' 'N-ZA-Mn-za-m' < data.txt` |
| `tr 'a-z' 'A-Z' < file` | Convert lowercase to uppercase | `tr 'a-z' 'A-Z' < data.txt` |
| `tr 'A-Z' 'a-z' < file` | Convert uppercase to lowercase | `tr 'A-Z' 'a-z' < data.txt` |
| `tr -d 'set' < file` | Delete specific characters from file | `tr -d '0-9' < data.txt` |
| `tr -s 'set' < file` | Squeeze repeated characters into one | `tr -s ' ' < data.txt` |

**How to Recognize Base64:**
- Long string of A-Z, a-z, 0-9, +, / characters
- Usually ends with `=` or `==` padding
- Length always a multiple of 4
- No spaces or special characters

**How to Recognize ROT13:**
- Looks like real words but completely scrambled
- Only contains regular alphabet letters and spaces
- Applying the same `tr` command twice returns original text

